risk
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\cx\to\cy$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R(f)=\ex\ell\left(f(x),y\right),
\]

\end_inset

where the expectation is over 
\begin_inset Formula $(x,y)\sim P_{\cx\times\cy}$
\end_inset

, a distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $\cx\times\cy$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
[unbiased estimate].
 Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 sampled i.i.d.
 from a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\reals$
\end_inset

.
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=\ex x$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim P$
\end_inset

.
 Then the mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{x}=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is an unbiased estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ex\bar{x}=x$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly, the sample variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is an unbiased estimate for 
\begin_inset Formula $\var\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 You should be able to easily verify these facts fairly easily.
 
\end_layout

